06338nam a22006975i 9780774855037DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072006xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748550377 a10.59962/97807748550372doi  a(DE-B1597)661331  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBQ286bG35 2006eb 7aREL0070002bisacsh04a294.3093400aGandharan Buddhism :bArchaeology, Art, and Texts /ced. by Pia Brancaccio, Kurt Behrendt. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b110 b&w illustrations, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsian Religions and Society00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPrologue: Some Debating Points on Gandhāran Buddhism and Kuṣāṇa History -- tArchaeology -- tRecent Archaeological Research in Gandhāra: The New Evidence -- tBuddhist Presence in the Urban Settlements of Swāt, Second Century BCE to Fourth Century CE -- tRelic Shrines of Gandhāra: A Reinterpretation of the Archaeological Evidence -- tTexts -- tPilgrimage Route Changes and the Decline of Gandhāra -- tNew Manuscript Sources for the Study of Gandhāran Buddhism -- tArt -- tBodhisattvas in Gandhāran Art: An Aspect of Mahāyāna in Gandhāran Buddhism -- tThe Nature and Use of the Bodily Relics of the Buddha in Gandhara -- tGateways to the Buddha: Figures under Arches in Early Gandhāran Art -- tA Gandhāran Relief with Two Scenes from Buddha’s Life -- tLocal Crafts in Early Gandhāran Art -- tĀnanda and Vajrapāni: An Inexplicable Absence and a Mysterious Presence in Gandhāran Art -- tDesign Diversity in Kaniska’s Buddha Coins -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe ancient region of Gandhara, with its prominent Buddhist heritage, has long fascinated scholars of art history, archaeology, and textual studies. Discoveries of inscriptions, text fragments, sites, and artworks in the last decade have added new pieces to the Gandharan puzzle, redefining how we understand the region and its cultural complexity. The essays in this volume reassess Gandharan Buddhism in light of these findings, utilizing a multidisciplinary approach that illuminates the complex historical and cultural dynamics of the region. By integrating archaeology, art history, numismatics, epigraphy, and textual sources, the contributors articulate the nature of Gandharan Buddhism and its practices, along with the significance of the relic tradition. Contributions by several giants in the field, including Shoshin Kuwayama, John Rosenfield, and the late Maurizio Taddei, set the geographical, historical, and archaeological parameters for the collection. The result is a productive interdisciplinary conversation on the enigmatic nature of Gandharan Buddhism that joins together a number of significant pieces in a complex cultural mosaic. It will appeal to a large and diverse readership, including those interested in the early Buddhist religious tradition of Asia and its art, as well as specialists in the study of South and Central Asian Buddhist art, archaeology, and texts. A Buddha Dharma Kyokai Foundation Book on Buddhism and Comparative Religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist).2bisacsh1 aBehrendt, Kurt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBehrendt, Kurt, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrancaccio, Pia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrancaccio, Pia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBrown, Robert L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca